        <NamedIndividual IRI="#Vulnerability_Brokers"/>
    </Declaration>
    <Declaration>
        <NamedIndividual IRI="#Vulnerability_Intelligence"/>
    </Declaration>
    <Declaration>
        <NamedIndividual IRI="#Vulnerability_Researchers"/>
    </Declaration>
    <Declaration>
        <NamedIndividual IRI="#Windows_Management_Instrumentation"/>
    </Declaration>
    <Declaration>
        <NamedIndividual IRI="#Zero_Days"/>
    </Declaration>
    <Declaration>
        <NamedIndividual IRI="#eCommerce_Sites"/>
    </Declaration>
    <Declaration>
        <NamedIndividual IRI="#Gather_Victim_Information_%28Behavioral%29"/>
    </Declaration>
    <Declaration>
        <NamedIndividual IRI="#Search_Open_Websites%2FDomains"/>
    </Declaration>
    <Declaration>
        <AnnotationProperty IRI="#appEdgeDescription"/>
    </Declaration>
    <Declaration>
        <AnnotationProperty IRI="#appEdgeDescriptionReversed"/>
    </Declaration>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Accomplice"/>
        <Class IRI="#Role_Player"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Botnets"/>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#CommonPatternPhase"/>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern_Phase"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#CompositePatternPhase"/>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern_Phase"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Credential_and_Identity_Artifacts"/>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Crimeware"/>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Crimeware"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal>Crimeware is a broad category of malicious tools and software designed to enable or automate various forms of cybercrime. This class includes phishing kits, which simplify the creation of fake websites and emails to steal credentials, and infostealers, which are malware designed to extract sensitive information such as passwords, credit card details, and browser data. These tools are often sold as standalone products or bundled with additional features to maximize their effectiveness.

Other common crimeware includes Remote Access Trojans (RATs), which allow attackers to gain full control over a victim&apos;s device, and antivirus evasion tools, which help malware bypass detection by security software. Many crimeware offerings are equipped with user-friendly interfaces, automation capabilities, and even customer support, making them accessible to both skilled and novice cybercriminals. Some tools are sold as &quot;malware-as-a-service,&quot; allowing buyers to rent or subscribe to crimeware without needing technical expertise.

The availability of crimeware in underground marketplaces has significantly lowered the barrier to entry for cybercrime, enabling a wide range of malicious activities, from financial fraud to corporate espionage. These tools are often updated and customized to evade modern security measures, making them a persistent threat to individuals, businesses, and governments. By commoditizing cybercrime, crimeware has become a cornerstone of the underground economy.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Crimeware"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal>Crimeware refers to malicious software and tools sold in the cybercrime underground to facilitate illegal activities like data theft, fraud, and system compromise.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Dark_Platforms"/>
        <Class IRI="#Platform"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Dark_Platforms"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Explicitly designed for or dominated by illicit activities, often operating on the dark web or through anonymizing technologies like Tor. These platforms cater to cybercriminals by providing marketplaces for illegal goods and services (e.g., drugs, weapons, stolen data), forums for hacking tools and techniques, and services like Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS). Examples include dark web marketplaces (e.g., AlphaBay), carding sites, and illicit cryptocurrency exchanges. These platforms are entirely unregulated and intentionally hidden, making them central to the cybercrime ecosystem.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Dark_Platforms"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Explicitly designed for or dominated by illicit activities, often operating on the dark web or through anonymizing technologies.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Deceptive_Platforms"/>
        <Class IRI="#Platform"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Deceptive_Platforms"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Deceptive_Platforms are not genuine marketplaces or service providers; rather, they present false fronts to lure users into scams. Common examples include sham cryptocurrency exchanges, fake e-commerce sites, and bogus financial advisory platforms. By mimicking design elements from legitimate platforms—such as realistic dashboards, support features, or brand aesthetics—these sites or apps establish a veneer of trust that entices victims to deposit funds or share sensitive data. Unlike platforms designed to facilitate cybercriminals’ own transactions or communications, Deceptive_Platforms target outsiders (i.e., potential victims), intending to steal assets or personal information under the false promise of legitimate business, investment, or other interactions.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Deceptive_Platforms"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Websites, apps, or other online services deliberately fabricated to appear credible, but which exist primarily to deceive and exploit unsuspecting victims.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Disruption"/>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Economic_Impact"/>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Economic_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">The Economic Impact class covers harms involving financial loss or economic damage. Instances represent things like direct loss of money, theft, fines, or increased operational expenses caused by an event phase. For example, stolen funds or payment of remediation costs are modeled under this class.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Economic_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms related to financial losses or costs resulting from an event.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Environmental_Impact"/>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Environmental_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms to the physical environment or natural resources. Instances might include pollution, damage to facilities that affects ecosystems, or other ecological side-effects of a cyber event. In practice, this is used when an event’s consequences harm the environment or resource infrastructure.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Environmental_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms that affect the natural environment or ecological resources.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Extortion"/>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Facilitator"/>
        <Class IRI="#Role_Player"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Financial_Services"/>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#General_Victim_Groups"/>
        <Class IRI="#Victim"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#General_Victim_Groups"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">High-level categories of victims (such as employees, customers, or institutions) that are not tied to any one attack. Instances represent roles or broad population groups. This class is used when a phase affects a general class of victims, for example “financial institutions” or “individual users” in the ecosystem.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#General_Victim_Groups"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Broad groups of victims not tied to a specific Pattern or Phase.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Geopolitical_Impact"/>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Geopolitical_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms affecting governments, nations, or global stability. Examples are cyber actions that escalate to international incidents, state-sponsored attacks causing diplomatic issues, or any effect on national security systems. Use this class for harms that have political or geopolitical consequences beyond the local organization.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Geopolitical_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms related to national security or international political stability.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Grey_Platforms"/>
        <Class IRI="#Platform"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Grey_Platforms"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Grey platforms occupy a middle ground between legality and criminality. They may operate legally but often lack robust oversight, exploit regulatory loopholes, or intentionally provide services that are attractive to cybercriminals. Examples include unregulated or offshore cryptocurrency exchanges, bulletproof hosting providers (which resist takedown requests), privacy-focused tools like encrypted messaging apps, and cryptocurrency mixers/tumblers that anonymize transactions. These platforms are not inherently illegal but are frequently used to facilitate cybercrime, such as laundering stolen funds or hosting malicious content.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Grey_Platforms"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Operate legally but are often unregulated, have weak compliance measures, or are intentionally permissive, making them attractive to cybercriminals.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
        <Class abbreviatedIRI="owl:Thing"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">All types of negative consequences that victims can suffer during or after a pattern phase. It includes concrete harms (like financial losses or operational disruptions) as well as broader effects (business or societal impacts). Each subclass of Harms (such as Economic Impact or Psychological Impact) represents a specific dimension of harm, allowing the model to capture both immediate and downstream damages associated with cyber events.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Categories of negative outcomes or impacts experienced by victims during a pattern phase.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Illicit_Access_Products"/>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Illicit_Access_Products"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">The Illicit Access Products subclass encompasses commodities that provide unauthorized entry into computer systems, networks, or accounts. These products are typically acquired through illicit means such as exploiting vulnerabilities, phishing, credential stuffing, or deploying malware. Once obtained, they are sold within underground marketplaces to other threat actors, including ransomware operators, data exfiltration groups, and espionage actors.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Illicit_Access_Products"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Unauthorized access credentials and control mechanisms illicitly obtained and sold to facilitate further cybercriminal activities.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Informational_Impact"/>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Informational_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms involving information assets. It includes the loss of confidentiality (exposed data), loss of integrity (corrupted or altered data), and loss of availability (denial of access). This class captures core information-centric consequences of an event, such as sensitive files being breached or data being destroyed.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Informational_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms to data integrity, confidentiality, or availability</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Infrastructure_Services"/>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Infrastructure_Services"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Infrastructure Services encompass a range of commodities and offerings in the cybercrime underground that provide the technical backbone for malicious operations. These services include bulletproof hosting, which allows threat actors to host malicious content, such as phishing pages, malware, or command-and-control servers, without fear of takedown. Additionally, domain registration services for lookalike or malicious domains are often offered with anonymity and leniency toward abuse.

Another key component of infrastructure services is proxy and VPN providers, including residential proxy services, which allow attackers to mask their location and appear as legitimate users. These services are critical for evading detection, bypassing geofencing, and conducting activities like credential stuffing or web scraping. Some providers even offer &quot;clean&quot; IP pools to avoid triggering security alerts.

These services are essential for enabling and sustaining cybercriminal campaigns, as they provide the anonymity, reliability, and scalability needed for operations. By outsourcing infrastructure needs to specialized providers, threat actors can focus on their core activities, such as phishing, fraud, or ransomware deployment, while relying on robust and resilient infrastructure to support their attacks.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Infrastructure_Services"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Infrastructure Services in the cybercrime underground provide the foundational tools and resources, such as hosting, proxies, and VPNs, to support malicious activities.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Legitimate_Platforms"/>
        <Class IRI="#Platform"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Legitimate_Platforms"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Entities that operate within legal and regulatory frameworks, providing lawful services to users. These platforms are not designed for illicit purposes but may be exploited by cybercriminals due to their widespread use and accessibility. Examples include banks, financial institutions, regulated cryptocurrency exchanges, payment processors, and social media or dating platforms. While they implement compliance measures like Know Your Customer (KYC) and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) protocols, their large user bases and global reach make them occasional targets for fraud, phishing, and money laundering.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Legitimate_Platforms"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Operate within legal frameworks, comply with regulations, and are not inherently designed for illicit purposes but may be exploited by cybercriminals.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Market"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal>Market is a class of entities that represent informal or unstructured trading &apos;market&apos; within underground ecosystems. A Market entity is linked to an arbitrary number of Role Players, Platforms, and Products and Services which are components used to describe the market and indicate how it contributes to the creation of a given Pattern Phase. A Market can also be linked to other Markets or Pattern Phases.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Market"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">A market is a structured ecosystem where buyers and sellers interact to exchange specific types of products and services via different platforms.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Market_or_Supply_Chain"/>
        <Class IRI="#Market"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Market_or_Supply_Chain"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">&quot;Market or Supply Chain&quot; are a kind of Market that are essentially market places or supply chains for products or services in the underground</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Operational_Impact"/>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Operational_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms that affect an organization’s day-to-day functioning. Instances are things like service outages, halted production lines, or interrupted workflows caused by an event phase. This class is used when a cyber incident directly impairs the normal operations of a business or system.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Operational_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms that disrupt normal business operations or processes.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal>A Pattern is a structured model representing a recurrent, recognizable manifestation of illicit, harmful cyber-dependent or cyber-enabled activity, encompassing multiple, diverse Pattern Phases that collectively express a coherent operational or business model, without implying criminality or attribution.

1. “Recognizable” - its been noted and described.
2. “Recurrent” - its happening often enough in a consistent manner to be called a Pattern.
3. Cyber-enabled or Cyber-dependent - must have a significant cyber component.
4. Illicit - forbidden by law, rules or customs, adverse -  negative impact on the victim, exploitative - produces advantage or gain for the perpetrator.
5. Complex business or operational model -  cannot be simplified to a TTP or Pattern Phase.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Cybercrime patterns represent the recurring methods, schemes, or strategies used by cybercriminals to achieve malicious objectives, such as theft, extortion, or disruption.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern_Phase"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal>Pattern Phases describe a single, recognizable, illicit, adverse or exploitative cyber-dependent or cyber-enabled activity.

It describes a unique set of four interconnected core elements: Adversary (Role Player), Capability (Threat Action), Infrastructure (Platform or Commodity), and Victim (Impact).
A Pattern Phase is based on a Diamond Event - the multi-dimensional description of a complete &quot;phase&quot; in a pattern, while a Threat Action is a specific technical action that the role player performs during that phase.

Pattern Phases represent the phases or &quot;steps&quot; taken by an actor to form a Pattern. One Event can be associated with one or more Patterns.
A Pattern Phase can also be linked to a &quot;Cluster&quot; / “Market”, when the cluster trades an activity.
Pattern Phases can be &quot;chained&quot; together in sequences, when one Pattern Phase includes other, common Events.

USAGE NOTE: Some Pattern Phases (especially technical) occur commonly across diverse Patterns; they are labelled &quot;Common&quot; and can be re-used.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern_Phase"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal>Represents a single interaction between an adversary, their capability, the infrastructure they use, and the victim they target, forming the atomic unit of analysis in intrusion investigations.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Payment_Instruments"/>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Payment_Instruments"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Payment Instruments represent the various forms of value that enable illicit transactions, extortion, and money‐laundering in underground markets. These include digital currencies (for example, Bitcoin or Monero), government‐issued legal tenders (such as US Dollars or Euros), prepaid or stored‐value cards and vouchers (for instance, Amazon or iTunes gift cards), electronic wallets and payment apps (like PayPal, Venmo, or Alipay), informal money‐transfer systems (such as bank wires, money orders, or hawala networks), alternative value stores (including precious metals, high‐value retailer vouchers, or prepaid mobile credit), and virtual or in‐game assets (for example, NFTs or in‐game currency). Threat Actors, Criminal Service Providers, and Facilitators routinely buy, sell, or convert these instruments to fund ransomware payouts, purchase hacking infrastructure, and obscure the provenance of stolen proceeds. By classifying Payment Instruments as a subclass of Products and Services, Atlas captures how value flows through money‐laundering operations, ransom negotiations, and underground trades, allowing analysts to trace the movement of illicit funds across multiple modalities.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Payment_Instruments"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Mediums of exchange—such as cryptocurrencies, fiat currencies, gift cards, prepaid cards, electronic wallets, and other value‐transfer instruments—that actors acquire, trade, and launder within the cybercrime ecosystem.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Perpetrator"/>
        <Class IRI="#Role_Player"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Physical_Impact"/>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Physical_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Real-world damage resulting from an event. This can include destruction of hardware, damage to facilities, or even physical injury to people if a cyber event creates safety hazards. Use this class when an incident’s effects extend beyond digital data into the physical environment.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Physical_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms that cause physical damage to people or property.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Platform"/>
        <Class abbreviatedIRI="owl:Thing"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Platform"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal>Contains generally-described technology services, applications or platforms that are used to facilitate a Pattern Phase, transaction, exchange of value or communication between role players.

Platforms can be linked to Markets and Pattern Phases.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
        <Class abbreviatedIRI="owl:Thing"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal>Products and Services encompass tools, capabilities, goods, or services used within Pattern Phases to enable, facilitate, or support cybercrime activity. They are traded on Marketplaces and may be linked to both Pattern Phases and Marketplaces.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Psychological_Impact"/>
        <Class IRI="#Harm"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Psychological_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Emotional or mental harm experienced by victims. Instances include anxiety, trauma, loss of trust, or stress caused by an event phase. For example, a victim experiencing fear or distress after personal information is stolen would fall under this class.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Psychological_Impact"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Harms affecting mental health or well-being of individuals.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#ReconnaissanceAndOpenSourceIntelligence"/>
        <Class IRI="#Products_and_Services"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Role_Player"/>
        <Class abbreviatedIRI="owl:Thing"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Role_Player"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal>A Role Player represents an actor that fulfills a specific role within the cybercrime ecosystem, participating in activities, transactions, or operations that contribute to a Pattern Phase.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Scams_and_Fraud"/>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#SpecificPatternPhase"/>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern_Phase"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Specific_Victim_Groups"/>
        <Class IRI="#Victim"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Specific_Victim_Groups"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Concrete categories of victims without reference to a single Phase or Pattern. For example, instances might be particular industry sectors, asset owners, or known target types. This class helps identify who could be affected by a phase, such as ‘personal data owners’ or ‘bank customers</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Specific_Victim_Groups"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Specific types of victims (e.g., individuals or organizations) categorized broadly.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Tactic"/>
        <Class abbreviatedIRI="owl:Thing"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Technique"/>
        <Class abbreviatedIRI="owl:Thing"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Theft"/>
        <Class IRI="#Pattern"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Underground_Managed_Service"/>
        <Class IRI="#Market"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Underground_Managed_Service"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">&quot;Underground Managed Service&quot; is a kind of Market that act like businesses to deliver managed or continuous services (probably on a subscription basis) to other Role Players within the underground economy</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Underground_Service"/>
        <Class IRI="#Market"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Underground_Service"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">&quot;Underground Service&quot; are a kind of Market that act like businesses to deliver specific services to other Role Players within the underground economy</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Victim"/>
        <Class abbreviatedIRI="owl:Thing"/>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Victim"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#longDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">Entities that can be targeted or affected in a pattern phase. Instances represent individuals, organizations, systems, or groups that suffer harm or attacks. Subclasses specify whether they are general victim groups, specific types of victims, or victims defined by particular attack patterns.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
    <SubClassOf>
        <Class IRI="#Victim"/>
        <DataHasValue>
            <DataProperty IRI="#shortDescription"/>
            <Literal xml:lang="en">An entity that is targeted or suffers harm in a Pattern Phase.</Literal>
        </DataHasValue>
    </SubClassOf>
