    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Pattern</IRI>
        <Literal xml:lang="en">A Pattern is a structured model representing a recurrent, recognizable manifestation of illicit, harmful cyber-dependent or cyber-enabled activity, encompassing multiple, diverse Pattern Phases that collectively express a coherent operational or business model, without implying criminality or attribution.

1. “Recognizable” - its been noted and described.
2. “Recurrent” - its happening often enough in a consistent manner to be called a Pattern.
3. Cyber-enabled or Cyber-dependent - must have a significant cyber component.
4. Illicit - forbidden by law, rules or customs, adverse -  negative impact on the victim, exploitative - produces advantage or gain for the perpetrator.
5. Complex business or operational model -  cannot be simplified to a TTP or Pattern Phase.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:label"/>
        <IRI>#Pattern</IRI>
        <Literal xml:lang="en">Pattern</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#PatternPhaseSequence</IRI>
        <Literal xml:lang="en">This property conveys the position of a Pattern Phase in the sequence of events linked to a Pattern. Where the Pattern Phase is &quot;common&quot; - that is shared across multiple Patterns - this property should be left blank. In that case, the relative position of the Event in the sequence of events linked to a Pattern should be determined by &quot;blanks&quot; left in the sequence. E.g. If a Pattern links to Events with sequence numbers 1,2, and 4, then an Event with a blank sequence would be assumed to assume position 3 in the sequence of events.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:label"/>
        <IRI>#PatternPhaseSequence</IRI>
        <Literal xml:lang="en">PatternPhaseSequence</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Pattern_Phase</IRI>
        <Literal>Pattern Phases describe a single, recognizable, illicit, adverse or exploitative cyber-dependent or cyber-enabled activity. In the Diamond Model of Intrusion Analysis, an Diamond Event is a discrete occurrence that connects at least two of the model&apos;s core elements: Adversary, Capability, Infrastructure, and Victim. Each event represents a specific action or interaction, such as an adversary deploying malware (Capability) through a phishing email (Infrastructure) to compromise a victim&apos;s system. Events are the building blocks of the model, enabling analysts to break down complex attacks into smaller, understandable components.

Events are not isolated; they are part of a larger sequence of actions that adversaries use to achieve their objectives. For example, an event might involve an adversary using a fake website (Infrastructure) to steal credentials from a victim, which is then followed by another event where the adversary uses those credentials to access the victim&apos;s account. By analyzing these events, investigators can identify Pattern, infer adversary intent, and trace the progression of an attack.

Each event in the Pattern Phase is enriched with meta-features such as time, phase, and methodology, which provide additional context. These meta-features help analysts understand when the event occurred, how it fits into the broader attack lifecycle, and what techniques were used. By linking events together into activity threads, analysts can reconstruct the full narrative of an intrusion, enabling better detection, response, and prevention strategies.

USAGE NOTE: Some Pattern Phases (especially technical) occur commonly across diverse Patterns; they are labelled &quot;Common&quot; and can be re-used.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:label"/>
        <IRI>#Pattern_Phase</IRI>
        <Literal xml:lang="en">Pattern Phase</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:seeAlso"/>
        <IRI>#Pattern_Phase</IRI>
        <IRI>https://apps.dtic.mil/sti/citations/ADA586960</IRI>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <IRI>#Payment_Instruments</IRI>
        <Literal xml:lang="en">This class contains mediums of exchange—such as cryptocurrencies, fiat currencies, gift cards, prepaid cards, electronic wallets, and other value‐transfer instruments—that actors acquire, trade, and launder within the cybercrime ecosystem.</Literal>
