    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <AbbreviatedIRI>owl:Thing</AbbreviatedIRI>
        <Literal>The Cybercrime Ontology seeks to develop a framework that represents a systemic overview of the cybercrime landscape, including its key elements and interrelations. While the Ontology will map key cybercrime elements (threat actor roles, methods, tooling, etc), the Ontology also seeks to incorporate a “victim element” that records the different types of impact that victims of cybercrime experience.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:comment"/>
        <AbbreviatedIRI>owl:Thing</AbbreviatedIRI>
        <Literal>The framework aims to become an informative tool for a wide range of audiences that may use it in different ways:
Cybercrime Atlas Research &amp; Mapping: The Cybercrime Ontology will be our common language, a tool to present output of our work and a map that guides our understanding of the cybercrime landscape, helping us identify potential further research avenues or choke points for disruption.
Law Enforcement Agencies: They could use the taxonomy to ingest and communicate the intelligence with the Cybercrime Atlas, have a wider understanding of the cybercrime landscape and identify choke points for disruption.
Policy makers: They could use it to identify regulatory and legislative gaps. For instance, the representation of the impact for victim’s could help derive areas of improvement.
Cybersecurity Community: The Ontology will serve to understand and communicate important aspects of cybercrime and the cybercrime ecosystem and guide further research. Additionally, through our experience, we hope to prepare a blueprint that guides similar projects.</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
    <AnnotationAssertion>
        <AnnotationProperty abbreviatedIRI="rdfs:label"/>
        <AbbreviatedIRI>owl:Thing</AbbreviatedIRI>
        <Literal>Atlas Cybercrime Ontology</Literal>
    </AnnotationAssertion>
</Ontology>



